This is my third year acknowledging Advent and my first year fully leaning into it. The idea of making room for–and intentionally sitting with–longing and anticipation has been grounding for me, and I feel like healing waits for me here. For many of us. 🫶🏾

Hope in the Scriptures isn’t just “wishing for the best.” There were people suffering under the very REAL weight of oppressive regimes, looking back at how God delivered His people in the past and anticipating that He would do it again in the future. They weren’t just hoping He would “arrive.” They were hoping He would set them free. 

Advent sits in the tension of what has been and what will be. It’s the promise that liberation will follow suffering. And it’s the reminder that even though what I’m waiting for hasn’t happened yet, I’ve seen it happen before, and I believe it will happen again.

This is hope. 🤗

Peace will not leave us in ruins. 🕊️

The peace we meditate on during Advent is “shalom,” a state of completeness or wholeness. It’s a promise that restoration follows brokenness.

This peace is better than calmness. All can be quiet and still be in turmoil. A country can proclaim a calm “peace” while its people still suffer within its borders. 

True peace is more than deciding to stop breaking things. It’s fixing what’s broken and making it whole again. I love how Dr. King puts it:

“Peace is not merely the absence of this tension, but the presence of justice...

If peace means a willingness to be exploited economically, dominated politically, humiliated and segregated, I dont want peace...

Jesus says in substance, I will not be content until justice, goodwill, brotherhood, love, yes, the kingdom of God are established upon the earth. This is real peace. Peace is the presence of positive good.”

May peace be with you, too, and restore whatever might be broken in you. 🏡 ✌🏾

Empathy laces up her boots 🥾🤍

If you’re experiencing a hard winter season, I’m so sorry. You are seen. You are not alone.

“If you can't fly then run, if you can't run then walk, if you can't walk then crawl, but whatever you do you have to keep moving forward.” – Martin Luther King, Jr. ✨

Speed is not the focus. You may wish you were further along by now, but you have not been left behind. My hope for you in this next year is that you just keep going–and that along the way, you find rest, peace, healing, and wholeness.

Forward is forward is forward 💚

P.S. if you want a hand with reflecting and looking ahead to the new year, there’s a free guide for you at the link in my bio

Choose a spine that speaks to you, and swipe to get a full work by Dr. King to sit with this week. Feel free to share what sticks out to you in the comments! 📚 I’ve linked to all of the full works in my bio.

Dr. King’s work is both a challenge and a healing balm. Yes, many people reduce this day to quotes… but many others genuinely want to be reminded that justice isn’t completely elusive and change is still possible.

Whether you’re disappointed with the state of racial justice in 2023 or you’ve grown complacent and cold within recent years, there’s something in his work and words for all of us. Spend time sitting with some of it. Read in context, in its entirety. Realign. Renew your commitments. Bring it to life in your daily journey. 

It all still matters. 🖤

I haven’t done an intro in over a year at least, so here are 10 facts about me that you may or may not know! Let me know if we have anything in common!!

1. I’m an illustrator, graphic designer, speaker, & consultant. I talk about anti-racism, creative entrepreneurship, & living a life of good work. Justice ain’t a trend for me so I take breaks when needed & I’m often very frustrated but this is gonna be my life’s work 🤷🏾‍♀️

2. I’m a 2023 bride!! I’m in love and getting married in March to my best friend in the whole world.

3. I found out in therapy this month that I have adult ADHD. It explains so much. So there’s that.

4. I’m Disney-obsessed. They’re my #1 dream client. My favorite movie is Monsters Inc!

5. I watch video game play-throughs in my free time sometimes 🎮 I like thrillers and the ones where you choose your own path/make decisions under pressure!!

6. My biggest pet peeve is slow, wet chewing, where I can hear everything going on in ya mouth 😂 just horrible.

7. After years of recovering from spiritual abuse from a church system, I’ve finally found a new church home. We thank God.

8. I closed my shop last year, and while it was a lil sad, it was also the best decision I could’ve made for myself. I plan to revisit it this year 😉

9. I LOVE period pieces and historical dramas. Bonus points if racism is completely ignored and I can bask in the glory of Black people in power. Bridgerton season 2 had me GASPING

10. I’ve been working on my biggest project ever for months and months and I think I can finally share about it next month! YAY! 

Ok I think we are all caught up now 😊 thanks for being here!

It’s with GREAT JOY that I announce my debut BOOK and multi-year publishing deal with @andrewsmcmeel! Introducing “A Heart on Fire,” 100 Meditations on Loving Your Neighbors Well ❤️‍🔥

I sought to write the book I needed–one that would encourage me each day to live a life poured out, in both word and deed. Based on my poem of the same name, A Heart on Fire is filled with heart-warming meditations, pointed truths, and practical steps for making the pursuit of justice a daily practice. 

This book is built on a framework I call the Ten Pillars of a Life of Good Work, and is split into sections on love, creativity, justice, awareness, hope, community, consistency, empathy, honesty, and redemption. Each of the 100 meditations is accompanied by a hand-drawn illustration or infographic 🎨

This book quite literally holds my heart. The process was incredibly difficult, yet beautiful and deeply holy. Whether you’re still in the early stages of incorporating these concepts into your daily life or you feel like you are crumbling under the weight of this heavy work, I pray this book lights a new fire in you that will strengthen you for the days to come. 

This book is for all of us: the activists, the stay-at-home parents, the students, and the everyday advocates. May it challenge you and cheer you on. 🎈🎉

You can pre-order A Heart on Fire today at the link in my bio (and that would mean the WORLD to me!!) I also gotta thank my agent @annette.bourland for being so lovely, patient, and supportive throughout this whole process.

Thank you so much for all the love on yesterday’s announcement! When we cling tightly to all that is good & right & just, our good work in response will be a natural outflow.

Unity isn’t synonymous with togetherness. We can all be in the same book and yet not be on the same page 📖 

Unity also isn’t a guaranteed result of diversity. We can all be in the same boat and yet want to sail in different directions (or even worse–some could want to sink the ship) 🛶 

Unity for change involves different people using different methods–yet moving in the same direction! Towards progress 🤗➡️

Yes, it’s normal to disagree on smaller things from time to time, but at the end of the day, unity relies on shared values and a common goal.

🧡 NEW SERIES! 🧡 

I’m sorry, but is it feeling WILD out here for anyone else? Truly? It often feels impossible to go about everyday life as parents, students, spouses, business owners, etc. while also caring about CHANGE. We want to end mass shootings, learn the truth about Black history, end the banning of our books, and so much more… yet we also want to thrive in our day-to-day lives without being overtaken by anxiety and hopelessness. 🌎 

Some of us are activists, but most of us are everyday advocates. In this new series, I want to share tips for living a life of advocacy in challenging seasons while also pulling insights from Dr. King and his “Letter from Birmingham Jail” that feels more and more relevant to our current culture as the days go by. 📝

I didn’t realize this until today, but 60 years ago on this day, he was arrested in Birmingham for peacefully marching against segregation, and he wrote the letter over the next several days. I truly didn’t plan for this overlap (I’ve been working on this for a while) but it feels so timely!! 

I hope this series brings some encouragement and direction for your journey toward change- whatever that looks like for you right now. 🧡

Also, so excited to push myself creatively with new colors & more constraint with this project! They say constraint fosters innovation. Excited to see!! 💡 

Comment with a “🌎” if you’ll be tuning in!!!!! 😊😊😊

#EverydayAdvocateSurvivalGuide

Criticism. It stings! And it’s sometimes necessary! But it’s often used as a distraction sent to throw you off course. Don’t let it!🪧 

It’s Day 1 of the Everyday Advocate Surivial Guide series, and we’re opening up with the way Dr. King opened his Letter from Birmingham Jail: clearing the air about why he wrote the letter in the first place. 

When working for change, you’ll inevitably be challenged by people who disagree with you. It’s crucial to be able to identify when criticism is fair & given in good faith vs when it’s an attack on your journey for justice (or just plain disrespect) 🤚🏾

There’s a difference between responding to objections raised by someone you respect vs. going back and forth with an anonymous online bully. 

We’ve got work to do. Having challenging conversations and receiving feedback is part of that work! Arguing back and forth? Maybe not 🤷🏾‍♀️ 

What are some of your boundaries for having hard conversations? Have any tips on constructive criticism? Leave a comment to share! 😊

#EverydayAdvocateSurvivalGuide

I went to a march today in Nashville led by faith leaders called Moral Monday to protest policies that haven’t been supporting human flourishing in our state. We advocated for healthcare, gun reform, ending voter suppression, living wages, and other crucial topics. Leaders from all over the country came to join in this call for justice.

One thing that really moved me (among many other things) was when Rev. Dr. Barber asked other leaders to circle around him, saying that “nobody will stand at this podium alone.” 💙

This is what Dr. King meant when he responded to the accusation of “outside agitators” coming into Birmingham to support the growing civil rights movement there. How can one be an outsider when “whatever affects one directly affects all indirectly”? We are all inescapably connected and need each other 🫶🏾

When the journey gets weary, ask yourself: how can I get reconnected to community? Have I been climbing alone? Who can I call, march with, or vent to?

We need each other every day. This is a reminder that will truly never get old. 🏔️ 

#EverydayAdvocateSurvivalGuide

When we fight against gun violence and racism, we’re working to shrink ALL the circles 🔴

When you understand the way issues are interconnected and how racism is so intricately weaved throughout many of our country’s issues, you can understand why it’s so urgent to call things what they are and work towards changing them.

Highlighting the racial implications of #RalphYarl’s shooting doesn’t make the tragedy “all about race” - it brings to light the fact that racism is always at work and exacerbating our most devastating issues. It makes finding solutions that much more urgent. 

And we mourn the loss of #KaylinGillis while understanding that working to shrink the impact of gun violence across the board is an act of justice that helps us all.

The fruit of these issues show themselves day after day, but the root remains the same. We can’t talk about Black history and systemic racism less, we can’t continue to avoid meaningful gun legislation, and we can’t get distracted by those who try to convince us otherwise.

root > fruit 🌳 

In our work, it’s easy to get caught up in:

🌼 back-and-forths & hot takes that spark good conversations but often lack solutions 
🍊 temporary fixes that mean well but are essentially putting band-aids  on gaping wounds 
🍃 being more focused on the effects of issues than the root causes

When you do good work with the understanding that our individual actions toward change should move in tandem with our collective uprooting of the systems preventing change, you’ll realize that:

🌳 you’re not alone in this work or solely responsible for fixing everything 
🌳 we can’t stop at band-aid solutions because the roots of the issues run deep 
🌳 not seeing immediate change shouldn’t cause you to give up because uprooting is the work of a lifetime

Don’t get stuck in the disappointment of what you currently see. We’re working to create a future that’s yet to be seen!! 😊🧡

#EverydayAdvocateSurvivalGuide

Society tries to pit historically excluded communities against each other– but we can never forget that we’re better together!! 💚 

If you’ve been seeing the news about the war against DEI and Black history in schools while also witnessing Asian American and Pacific Islander History being (finally!!) required learning in Florida, you may be wondering: well, why not require both? 📚 

The answer is found in the age-old story of racial triangulation (a framework by Claire Jean Kim, swipe for the original): AAPI communities consistently being used as a political wedge, resulting in the continued exclusion of both communities (while especially disadvantaging Black communities). 🚩

When one group is volarized (or exalted) over another, nobody wins. Harmful stereotypes like the “model minority myth” and the “perpetual foreigner” continue to deepen these divides.

So, we continue to push for Black history AND Asian American & Pacific Islander history to be taught in schools, because one victory shouldn’t be won at the expense of another. We also fight against these stereotypes that consistently weigh us down!

We’re not pawns. We’re people. 💚💚💚

For me, it was @ravensymone. For many little Black girls all over the world this weekend, it’s gonna be @hallebailey! 🫧

Representation truly opens up a whole new world!! 🐠🧜🏾‍♀️🐡🌊🔱

A helpful tip for a life of good work: celebrate every kind of win, big or small. And celebrate loudly!! It’ll help keep you going. See you at the movies 🥹

Updating this graphic from last year to show that book banning increased by over 38% in 2022- and that doesn’t even factor in 2023 yet😮

For clarity, this graph depicts the number of unique titles that were targeted for censorship of some kind over the past few years (info from @americanlibraryassociation). I did a whole breakdown on this phenomenon last year (saved it in a highlight!) 📕 

These numbers don’t even fully encapsulate what’s really going on out here. It’s not just books that are under attack, it’s whole ideas & the freedom to express them! And just like last year, Black and LGBTQIA+ communities are being disproportionately targeted by these censorship attempts.

Also, a note: moving a book out of one age group to another in school settings (especially if it was written for that age group & already deemed appropriate by the standard processes in place) is still taking away access to that book. A lot of this is happening outside of approved guidelines & established procedures. 👀 

A kid shouldn’t have to go through a whole request process with their librarian to be able to somehow track down & read books like the ABCs of Black History, Love to Langston, or The Hill we Climb. Barriers to accessibility creates inaccessibility! This is our HISTORY we’re talking about, and it MATTERS 🤎

pen.org/action has tons of practical ways that you can push back against these reckless book bans (that are often backed by no evidence & just pulled out of thin air) so you can make your voice heard! There’s also a lot of good happening in response to all of this, and I’m hoping to share some of those stories soon 🤩📖

Let’s break down an example of a complaint filed to get a book removed from a FL school. This one is The Hill we Climb by @amandascgorman 📕

30% of school book bans from the first half of this past school year were about race, racism, Black history, or authored by people of color (PEN America).

Dr. @ibramxk once stated that scholars and scientists discovered that by 3 years old, kids have an adult-like conception of race and are attaching negative qualities to dark-skinned people.

Is talking about justice inappropriate for younger age groups? Or is it just uncomfortable? ❤️

These words are hopeful and bring so much light. I want to spread similar hope & truth with my own words & books. Let’s keep the light on 💡

A lil’ Sunday sermon. “Revival” has been a tough word for me in the past. 🥴

I gave a talk recently called “Hopeful Reimagination” and shared about how a lot of the current attempts to roll back racial justice & civil rights efforts are basically remakes: attempts to bring us back to the “good ol’ days” of oppression. None of this is new or creative. Kind of like a poorly-done live action rendition of your favorite childhood movie — familiar, yet unmoving. 

Changemakers & those who work for justice are creative in nature. We’re in the business of reimagination, following in the footsteps of the Creator & attempting to make things new in the world around us. ✨

I’ve been in church spaces where people will claim “revival” while there’s all kinds of racism, misogyny, and abuse actively going on in the system. Instead of being true to the definition of revival- improving the condition or strength of things- it’s a lot of the same ol’ thang going on.

You’ll know if something is a remake vs. reimagination by it’s endgame. Have we improved the conditions and strength of our cities & communities? Have we voted to protect the civil rights of the historically excluded who are consistently under attack? Are we ending cycles of harm within our own walls? 🤔

Doing this work is difficult — yet we find hope that God is in the business of reimagination too. If you’re in spaces that have the appearance of “change” but are churning out the same outcomes of harm & injustice… take note. Move accordingly. 🙏🏾

🎥: @thewitnessbcc

This happens when a word gets stripped from its definition & context- whatever that may be- and gets warped into a catch-all for all sorts of ideas… eventually becoming a pejorative & an attack 🎯

You can’t have longevity in your work if you’re not listening to your body 🌡️ 

I might as well have ripped this page straight out of my journal and posted it! I’ve been on a personal journey of really coming home to myself and ending the cycle of self-destruction when it comes to my work. Even after seasons of burnout, I find myself still (from time to time) putting my body on the line for the sake of a deadline or a debate. Prioritizing the expectations of others over my own rest and leisure. 🫣

I’m in the process of loudly taking back the reigns of my own life. If a conversation is becoming abusive or violent, I don’t have to participate in it! If an ask feels misaligned, I can just say no without explanation! If something is draining me, I can move on from it and find something more lifegiving (or even- gasp- enjoyable!!) to do instead!

One part of this process involves me deciding on minimum/maximum thresholds for engaging in conversations (or even projects) related to my work. I define my “scope of engagement” as topics I’m well-versed in, have the capacity for, or am comfortable enough with to dive into with others deeply. Going “above” that means the convo/ask is deeper than my current knowledge or capacity. Going “below” that means the convo/ask is on more of a beginner level in a way that would take more capacity than I have to break down & explain/do.

Beyond that, I also factor in environments, tone, behaviors, and my personal well-being. I’ve mentally used this tool to help me navigate events I’m willing to speak at (or even attend 😂), comments I respond to on my posts, in-person convos, etc.

I’m sharing in case any of this is helpful for anyone else. Swipe for a blank version in case you wanna try it! 📝

Your body is on this journey with you, whether you acknowledge it or not. Burnout doesn’t just come from exhaustion- it can come from hurt and numbness too. Sooner or later, your body will let you know when it has reached its breaking point. Let’s try to avoid that as best we can 💙

We’re ❤️‍🔥 TWO WEEKS AWAY ❤️‍🔥 from A Heart on Fire’s release, and I wanted to share one of my favorite pieces from the book & part of the meditation that goes along with it:

“It can seem, at times, that we’re caught in an endless loop of trauma… our hearts feel stretched in multiple directions, our empathy begins to wear thin, and we scold ourselves for feeling the weight of compassion…

We must find a way to allow compassion to move through us without crushing us. One way to move toward this would be to divide the weight of it among those who walk with us through life. A sign of true community is the ability to collectively shoulder life’s heavy loads so that no single person is completely crushed. 🌎 

Another strategy for carrying compassion involves a dedication to personal well-being. When we prioritize our mental and physical health, spiritual practices, joyful, hobbies, and times of rest, we pour into ourselves and fill our own cups. Caring for our own bodies and minds keeps us steady and strong— and when it’s time to pour into others, we won’t have to do it at the expense of our own well-being.

When lifting a heavy box, there are automatic considerations: how heavy is it? Do I have the strength? Will I need help? How long am I carrying this? How far am I able to go? It would do us well to consider similar questions as we do compassion’s heavy lifting.” ❤️‍🔥📦

Sharing some raw thoughts with you. A sentiment that kept replaying in my mind over the weekend is the idea of “heartbreak making way for fertile ground.” This extremely difficult time that we’re processing through as a global community has left our hearts tender… and while we’re advocating for justice & calling for ceasefires, many of us are sitting in that brokenness. Yet that tender space can also be a place where new seeds of change can be planted. Not just hoping for it, but taking steps to reorient ourselves to what’s good & right & true by dedicating ourselves to new rhythms while we try to get through our days and all our current responsibilities.

You may have discovered that you haven’t been as in-tune with global news as you want to be (I know I’m not), yet now is a chance to plant that seed and tend to it by looking for unbiased outlets and seeing how you can create a new rhythm of being informed without being completely overwhelmed. Or you’re finding how important language is and how easily entire people groups can be dehumanized. You can plant this seed and tend to it by choosing to define your terms, remember context, & sprout that habit of avoiding harmful rhetoric as you discuss tough topics.

If you’re looking for something tangible as you make your way through this week, swipe for a blank chart that you can fill with 1-3 new rhythms to try dedicating yourself to. Keep leaning into compassion and gentleness and your heart for justice. It won’t stop the heartbreak, but it’ll hopefully give you a glimmer of hope that change is still possible because it’s happening within you. You’re living proof. 

You may not know exactly what next step to take, but it’s never a bad idea to be aware of this tenderness you’re currently experiencing and finding little ways to stay soft and open and dedicated to this good work. I’m right there with you.
Sending love to those of us aching with communal agony. Indifference will not protect us. Let it matter.

This is the meditation “True Peace” from my upcoming book A Heart on Fire, available everywhere on Tuesday, October 24 🥹❤️‍🔥: 

“Peace is not calmness. It is not automatically present when all is still. Consider the immediate aftermath of an earthquake or a powerful storm. Buildings have been destroyed, trees fell, and debris and rubble lie everwhere. Yes, all is quiet, but there is not peace–there’s devastation. Peace won’t be restored in the hearts of those affected until there’s repair and restoration, when their belongings are no longer scattered and their homes are inhabitable once again.

A false sense of peace can also show up in our relationships. The silence following a tense argument, apologies left unsaid, tip-toeing around a loved one so as to not awaken the sleeping giant of their rage. In working for justice, false peace can show up as the quiet acceptance of the status quo, where people have chosen calmness instead of the noise of progress.

We must seek peace in its truest form. Not the appearance of peace that comes from closing your heart to the world and its troubles. Peace is not found in absence, but in presence.

Peace isn’t just calmness or the end of a fight. It’s a complete restoration where all is made right. Peace requires repairing relationships, having uncomfortable conversations, and stirring the pot. The pursuit of peace may get messy, noisy, and chaotic, but those who work towards it are closer to peace than those who sit in quiet compliance with the mere appearance of it.”

Empathy is stretching work. It’s heavy and often overwhelming. But when faced with overwhelm, we have a few choices: we can do nothing, which changes nothing… we can be performative, which offers temporary satisfaction but fizzles out eventually… or we can focus our efforts on creating sustainable rhythms of action that allow us to bring our gifts to the table and make a difference, right where we’re planted, for the long-haul.

I want this book to be another tool that you collect along the way. I don’t have all the answers, but I do want you to feel empowered after each entry to go out and live a life of love like only you can. These days, we’re gonna need a LOT of it.

Forever grateful for your incredible support of A Heart on Fire so far. I wrote it for us… for today and for the days to come. I’m praying it’s both a comfort for your heart and a call to love ferociously. You’re needed now more than ever. 🌎❤️‍🔥

We’re feeling it now. The tugs on the strings that tie us together. From Palestine to Sudan, from Yemen to Congo, from Israel to Ukraine, the arms reaching out for freedom & refuge pull on our heartstrings. How could they not? This is the “inescapable network of mutuality, the single garment of destiny, the interrelatedness of all communities and states,” as Dr. King puts it.

Your soul should stir at the sight of injustice. Your heart should swell with empathy when witnessing oppression. If you’re feeling the need to draw nearer, listen closer, dig deeper… this is the proof of interconnection. The certainty of the strings.

This tug is asking something of you. Will you create? Write? March? Pray? Connect? Read? Call? Feel? Give? The decision is yours. It doesn’t always have to feel “big” to be meaningful. It doesn’t have to be “loud” to be heard. It doesn’t have to be public to be legitimate. It just has to be yours.

The beauty of this is, when I’m pulled one direction, you may be pulled in another. This is humanity. It’s how we cover ground. Don’t let your dissatisfaction with someone else’s response distract you from where your tug leads you. Just go. 

It all matters. It’s all felt. What a gift it is to be connected to each other.

01 | what do I do with all of this terrible news?

Today, I will let it inflate my capacity to love. I will allow my heart to expand beyond what it’s grown accustomed to. My love will know no bounds. I will flood this new space with their stories, their cries, their songs, and in response, will do what love requires. I will go where love sends me. I will bring love back home. I will stay soft, open, pliable… I will let this swelling heart make something new out of me.

02 | what do I do with all of this terrible news? 

What happens when we put on the perspective of the hurting and the vulnerable? Seeing the world through the lens of its heartbreak?

We are like witnesses called to the stand. The evidence of oppression multiplies. The hurting plead their case. Now you have seen. Will you testify?

03 | what do I do with all of this terrible news?

Where is hope in horror? Hope is the doctor holding the hand of a trembling patient. Hope is the smile of a cashier in the checkout line. Hope is protest. Hope is prayer. Hope lives in the keepers of light, those renewing our faith in humanity, who in doing their good work bear the image of the invisible God.

“Hope is being able to see that there is light despite all of the darkness.” — Archbishop Desmond Tutu

What does the good news say to all of this terrible news? 

I’ve never been at such a loss for words as I have been these last couple of months, so I’ve been clinging to living hope & advent promises. Promises of Immanuel, God with us. That in his name, all oppression shall cease. That trouble won’t last always… 

We can never forget that our hope in the eventual end of violence & war & loss should be coupled with our best efforts to make it so. The promise of living hope is not an invitation to cover our eyes or sit on our hands, but to align our hearts, our deeds, with the blessed Prince of Peace, and to prepare the way.

Thinking daily of the words of @munther_isaac: “The Child under the rubble. Immanuel God is with us in our pain and suffering. God in solidarity with the oppressed. The child of Bethlehem is our hope. For the children of Gaza and all victims of wars.” 🤍

This year’s FREE reflection guide is here! 🔥 And it looks a bit different than it used to!

Firstly, you might notice that there’s two of them! You get to choose which one is best for you! When prepping the guide, I thought about all of you who may still be reeling from the intensity of 2023 and aren’t ready to dive into dreaming about a new year quite yet. I took the original “A Good Look” guide, slowed it down, and added extra encouragement to it. There’s still a 2024 section but it’s more gentle and inward-focused. I call this version “The Ember Edition.”

Embers are what’s left after a fire has finished burning—but they’ve still got a glow about them. With time & attention, it’s quite possible that they can burn brightly once again. 

The other guide is closer to the original in that it’s a bit more cheery and joyful while giving you space to dream about the future. I call it “The Spark Edition.”

I also exchanged the “word of the year” content with some deeper & more intentional questions to help you brainstorm ways to live out your values in 2024. I still think choosing a word of the year is a lovely exercise, but I’m sensing a need to go a bit deeper to prep for the days ahead. It’s going to be a year unlike any other and it’ll require deep work from all of us.

Whichever one you choose, I hope this guide is one of many resources that helps you take a Good Look at where you’ve been and gives you hope for where you’re going. Link in bio! Check your promo folder if you don’t see it right away ❤️

I made two versions of the same end-of-year reflection guide (free to download at the link in my bio), and I wanted to highlight the Ember edition.

ember- a piece of wood or coal, etc. that continues to burn after a fire has no more flames; slowly dying or fading emotions, memories, ideas, or responses still capable of being revived ❤️‍🔥

If you’re ending the year wondering 1. What just happened or 2. Where in the world do I go from here… you’re not alone. I hope this 11-page reflection guide helps you begin to process where you’ve been and give you hope for where you’re going. This isn’t the end of your story. 🫶🏾

Do not feel guilty when moments of joy come to you as the world weeps. Joy isn’t naivete or cluelessness. It’s is a tool in your toolbox. It helps you find your rest & renewal, it aids your self/community care. It keeps you going. When joy rushes in, feel it fully, and be reminded of how important it is for others to feel it to. Spread it around as far as you can. Store those memories up. Joy is gas in your tank! Joy is proof that good still exists! Joy is hope for tomorrow! If joy comes knocking, let it in. 😊
